{{Military of the Ottoman Empire sidebar}} '''Croatian–Ottoman Wars''' ({{lang-tr|Osmanlı-Hırvatistan Savaşları|link=no}}, {{lang-hr|Hrvatsko-osmanski ratovi|link=no}}) can refer to one of the several conflicts between the [[Kingdom of Croatia (medieval)|Kingdom of Croatia]] (in [[Croatia in union with Hungary|Kingdom of Hungary-Croatia]] and in [[Habsburg Monarchy]]) and the [[Ottoman Empire]]: *[[Long Campaign]] (1443–1444) of the King [[Vladislaus II of Hungary]] *[[Hundred Years' Croatian–Ottoman War]], War for Croatia - a period of near constant mostly low-intensity warfare ("Small War") approximately 1493–1593 (from the [[Battle of Krbava Field]] to the [[Battle of Sisak]]) *[[Long War (Ottoman wars)|Long War]] (1593–1606) *[[Austro-Turkish War (1663–1664)]] *[[Great Turkish War]] (1683–1699) *[[Austro-Turkish War (1716–1718)]] *[[Austro-Turkish War (1787–1791)]] *[[Austro-Hungarian campaign in Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1878]] {{expand list|date=September 2012}}
The Kingdom of Croatia-Hungary gradually lost most of its territory on the eastern Adriatic coast to the Ottomans, leaving only the possessions of the [[Republic of Venice]] in [[Dalmatia]], for whom the Croats took part in the [[Ottoman–Venetian Wars]]. Of particular note for the history of Dalmatia was the [[Morean War]].
